# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cyrillization-of-chinese
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /ɤ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter Ъ.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, ⟨ӑ⟩ represents the mid central vowel [ə], as ⟨a⟩ in word "er**a**".
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [ə] (like the pronunciation of ⟨a⟩ in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the ⟨a⟩ in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in сӑтел *table*, /stel/.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter А̂ .
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. гла̂ва or кра̂к).
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̂ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̂ (U+0302).
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with ⟨аь⟩).
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa ⟨ә⟩ in modern Bashkir.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /æ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nʲ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tʲ/ or /dʲ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /ɐ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "Я".
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: брӓт or млāдä.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **глāвà**, **крāкà**, **овчāрè**, **ковāчè**, **юнāцѝ**, and **граждāнè**.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̄ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̄ (U+0304).
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Хрэстоматия вейска чили збюр выписов з рожных польских ауторов".
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Грамматыка е̨зыка польскего. На кляссэ̨ I". Въ друкарни р̌а̨довэй пр̌и коммиссыи р̌а̨довэй осьвецэня публичнэго.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Lithuania - Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Third Partition, Russian Revolution, League of Nations, Klaipėda | Britannica".
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/a-with-ring-above-cyrillic] A with ring above is used only in the alphabet of the Selkup language, where it represents the open-mid back rounded vowel /ɔ/ or the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] The **cyrillization of Chinese** is the transcription of Chinese characters into the Cyrillic alphabet.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] The **Palladius system** is the official Russian standard for transcribing Mandarin Chinese into Russian, with variants existing for Ukrainian, Belarusian and the various languages of Russia.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] It was created by Palladius Kafarov, a Russian sinologist and monk who spent thirty years in China in the nineteenth century.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] Other languages that use the Cyrillic script have systems designed for their own language.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] Note that because the Russian version of the Cyrillic alphabet has no letters for *dz* or *dzh* (although дз and дж are found in Bulgarian, and also ѕ and џ are found in Serbian and Macedonian Cyrillic), the digraphs цз and чж are used respectively.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] In composites, coda *ng* is transcribed нъ when the following syllable starts with a vowel.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] For example, the names of the cities of *Chang'an* and *Hengyang* are transcribed as Чанъань and Хэнъян.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] In syllables with no initial, *w* is transcribed as в in all cases except *wu*, transcribed as у.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] For example, the names of the cities of *Wuwei* (both Wuwei, Anhui and Wuwei, Gansu) and *Wanning* are transcribed as Увэй and Ваньнин.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] This table establishes correspondence between the Russian Palladius system together with the two Romanization systems most commonly used in English-speaking countries: Pinyin and Wade–Giles.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] It contains every syllable found in Ilya Oshanin's *Great Chinese–Russian Dictionary*.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] Note that the Palladius system does not distinguish between pinyin *luo* (as in 羅, *luó*) and the rare syllable *lo* (as in 咯, *lo*); both are written ло.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] The names of the cities of *Beijing* and *Nanjing* are transcribed as Пекин (instead of Бэйцзин) and Нанкин (instead of Наньцзин), much as *Peking* and *Nanking* were still used in English-speaking countries until recently.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] Hong Kong (pinyin: *Xiānggǎng*) may be both Сянган (*Xiānggǎng*) and Гонконг (*Hong Kong*); the latter is more common.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] In Russian borrowings from Chinese (such as place names), the syllable хуй (*hui*) is generally transcribed as хуэй (Huizu, Хуэйцзу) or occasionally хой (Anhui, Аньхой); this is because хуй is a taboo word for "penis" in Russian and several other Slavic languages.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] Dictionaries, however, may contain the unaltered spelling; as is found in Palladius' own dictionary from 1888, and Oshanin's *Great Chinese–Russian Dictionary*.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] Older documents contain variants мэн — мын, мэнь — мынь, фэн — фын, фэнь — фынь, пэн — пын, hence Aomen (Macao) is traditionally spelled Аомынь in Russian.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] Most modern texts contain э, with some exceptions.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] In composites, coda *ng* is transcribed н' when the following syllable starts with a vowel.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] For example, the names of the cities of *Chang'an* and *Hengyang* are transcribed as Чан'ань and Хен'ян.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] For example, the names of the cities of *Wuwei* and *Wanning* are transcribed as Увей and Ваньнін.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] This table establishes correspondence between the Ukrainian Palladius system together with the two Romanization systems most commonly used in English-speaking countries: Pinyin and Wade–Giles.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p01] The Serbian system is rather different from the Russian: for example, *j, q, zh* are transcribed as ђ, ћ, џ; the Serbian letters ј, љ, њ appear where the Russian system uses я, е, ю, й; final *n* and *ng* are н and нг.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p02] Zhège shì yīduàn yòng Xīlǐ'ěr zìmǔ xiě de Zhōngwén.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p02] {**Russian system:**} Ни хао ма? Чжэгэ ши идуань юн {Сили эр} {цзы му} се дэ Чжунвэнь.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p02] {**Ukrainian system:**} Ні хао ма? Чжеґе ши їдуань юн {Сілі ер} {цзи му} сє де Чжунвень.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p02] {**Belarusian system:**} Ні хаа ма? Чжэгэ шы ідуань юн {Сілі эр} {цзы му} се дэ Чжунвэнь.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p02] {**Bulgarian system:**} Ни хао ма? Джъгъ шъ идуан юн {Сили ер} {дзъ му} сие дъ Джунуън.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p02] {**Macedonian system:**} Ни хао ма? Џеге ши јидуан јонг {Шјили ер} {ѕи му} шјие де Џонгвен.
[src:cyrillization-of-chinese/cyrillization-of-chinese-p02] {**Serbian system:**} Ни хао ма? Џеге ши идуан јунг {Сили ер} {ци му} сје де Џунгвен.
